    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "type": "ContextOfUse",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "decisionConsequence": "High"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/vr-cpb-rh-index-experimental",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Relative Hemolysis Index Validation — FDA Pump Experimental Benchmark",
      "description": "The CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RH) was compared against experimentally measured hemolysis data from the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump operated across five flow-speed combinations (2.5 L/min at 2000 RPM, 3.5 L/min at 2500 RPM, 4.5 L/min at 3000 RPM, 5.0 L/min at 3500 RPM, and 6.0 L/min at 4000 RPM). Experimental measurements were conducted using a fresh ovine blood circuit with NIH normalized index of hemolysis protocol. The CFD model employed a power-law hemolysis damage accumulation model (Giersiepen–Wurzinger correlation) integrated along Lagrangian particle trajectories seeded at the pump inlet. Predicted RH values ranged from 0.71 to 0.94 across the five operating points, compared to experimentally observed values of 0.68 to 0.91, yielding a maximum absolute error of 4.3% and a mean signed error of +2.1%. All five predicted RH values satisfied RH < 1, consistent with the acceptance criterion. The simulation campaign was executed on a 128-core HPC cluster using ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 with a polyhedral mesh of 4.2 million cells validated for mesh independence at GCI < 2%. The experimental data were collected and processed by an independent biofluid mechanics laboratory under blinded conditions, with inter-operator variability below 3%. This result provides the primary quantitative evidence supporting the claim that the CFD model correctly identifies worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the CPB device.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-generic-pump-experimental-hemolysis"
    },
    {
